> this is not a bug ... your container is running on the default network which does not have dns enabled by default. this behavior matches docker. You either need to change the default network to enable dns or create a new network and have your container run on that.

Yes, you are right, however I have modified the default network configuration to have DNS enabled. Sorry I forgot to mention this at the beginning. My fault.

The essence of this issue report was the specific different behaviour of the container created using the systemd service and directly from command line using `podman run` command and this your answer does not explain.

There is my default network config:
```
{
   "cniVersion": "0.4.0",
   "name": "podman",
   "plugins": [
      {
         "type": "bridge",
         "bridge": "cni-podman0",
         "isGateway": true,
         "ipMasq": true,
         "mtu": 9000,
         "hairpinMode": true,
         "ipam": {
            "type": "host-local",
            "routes": [
               {
                  "dst": "0.0.0.0/0"
               }
            ],
            "ranges": [
               [
                  {
                     "subnet": "192.168.0.0/16",
                     "gateway": "192.168.0.1"
                  }
               ]
            ]
         }
      },
      {
         "type": "portmap",
         "capabilities": {
            "portMappings": true
         }
      },
      {
         "type": "firewall",
         "backend": ""
      },
      {
         "type": "tuning"
      },
      {
         "type": "dnsname",
         "domainName": "dns.podman",
         "capabilities": {
            "aliases": true
         }
      }
   ]
}
```
